(163, 1, '2021-10-04 05:20:56', '2021-10-04 05:20:56', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After the Second World War, the development of Canberra as the national capital was revitalised. The final move of central Commonwealth administration from Melbourne to Canberra involved thousands of people and a huge building program that included the creation of new suburbs as well as offices, schools and all the general city infrastructure. In its quest to meet the growing housing needs of Canberra at a time of extreme shortage of building materials the National Capital Planning and Development Committee was interested in available prefabricated houses. The transportation of a number of the Tocumwal houses and their installation in Ainslie and O’Connor was arranged. In Ainslie they were located in various streets amongst other types of housing, but in O’Connor they were established in a specific location that is now the O’Connor Tocumwal heritage precinct. Jim Perry was the builder who won the contract to install the houses in O’Connor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {"className":"is-style-wide"} -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator is-style-wide"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">On the road</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I lived near the Murray Valley Highway. I remember seeing houses in sections going along the highway on big trucks. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/on-the-road/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Unloading in O’Connor</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Alby and Dot Day moved into Hart Street in 1949. At this time the Tocumwal houses were still being put up in the O’Connor area.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/unloading-in-oconnor/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">‘Who ever thought we’d get a Tocumwal house!’</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>John Barty was employed as a carpenter on the construction of houses at the Tocumwal air force base. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/who-ever-thought-wed-get-a-tocumwal-house/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Owen Taverner – bricklayer – contract for 100 Tocumwal cottages in O’Connor</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Owen Taverner and his partners Billy Moore and Billy Goggin had the contract with Jim Perry to build the footings and chimneys.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/owen-taverner-bricklayer-contract-for-100-tocumwal-cottages-in-oconnor/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->', 'From Tocumwal to Canberra', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'from-tocumwal-to-canberra', '', '', '2021-10-04 13:41:40', '2021-10-04 13:41:40', '', 11, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?page_id=163', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(164, 1, '2021-10-04 05:20:56', '2021-10-04 05:20:56', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After the Second World War, the development of Canberra as the national capital was revitalised. The final move of central Commonwealth administration from Melbourne to Canberra involved thousands of people and a huge building program that included the creation of new suburbs as well as offices, schools and all the general city infrastructure. In its quest to meet the growing housing needs of Canberra at a time of extreme shortage of building materials the National Capital Planning and Development Committee was interested in available prefabricated houses. The transportation of a number of the Tocumwal houses and their installation in Ainslie and O’Connor was arranged. In Ainslie they were located in various streets amongst other types of housing, but in O’Connor they were established in a specific location that is now the O’Connor Tocumwal heritage precinct. Jim Perry was the builder who won the contract to install the houses in O’Connor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'From Tocumwal to Canberra', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '163-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-10-04 05:20:56', '2021-10-04 05:20:56', '', 163, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?p=164', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(165, 1, '2021-10-04 05:29:58', '2021-10-04 05:29:58', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We moved into Hart Street in November 1948. I was in hospital with my first born, then my husband was offered the house. He was questioned why he needed a four-bedroomed house with just one child and his reply was ‘future developments’ – which proved to be right as we subsequently had eight children. Our house was the first to be handed over and we were really pioneering. There was a small creek bed running through the back of the block, so much rock had to be dug out before a garden could be contemplated. We moved from there to Palmerston in April 1992 as the house and garden were becoming too much for us to manage as the children had all married and left home.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It wasn’t until some time in the 50s before the road was sealed and kerbs and guttering completed. I well remember the dust and heat on that occasion, not to mention the noise.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The ‘paddock’ at the top of the street was a great place for the children of the street – which were quite a lot – to get together, kick a football, ride their bikes and my sons tell me ‘meeting girls’. We had quite a few bonfires there on Cracker Night and the general community feeling was one of friendliness.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We made some improvements to our house, removing the large fireplace structure and the fuel stove in the kitchen in the 60s. Also having the outside of the house clad with artificial tile around the same time, although we see that the present owner removed this and it is once again the original fibro and weatherboard structure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Peg Hayes, Hart Street, 1948-1992 (contributed 1996)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'The first to be handed over', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-first-to-be-handed-over', '', '', '2021-10-04 05:29:58', '2021-10-04 05:29:58', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?p=165', 0, 'post', '', 0),
