s/?p=178', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(179, 1, '2021-10-04 07:15:37', '2021-10-04 07:15:37', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It rained a lot in that winter and the mud and dampness was a worry to everyone. Our driveway became an absolute bog and so Bruce contacted the Works Department about some kind of help with our drive. I might add that Canberra was only a small place in those days and mostly everyone knew or knew of, one another. Our request was granted. A large load of rocks was delivered to our driveway - as too was a sledgehammer with a little note from someone in the department with a great sense of humour - \'Good luck with the rocks Bruce\'!! So much for knowing someone in the Works Department.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Dorothy Holgate, Quinn Street, 1950-52 (contributed 1996)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '\'Good luck with the rocks, Bruce!\'', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'good-luck-with-the-rocks-bruce', '', '', '2021-10-04 07:15:37', '2021-10-04 07:15:37', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?p=179', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(180, 1, '2021-10-04 07:15:37', '2021-10-04 07:15:37', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It rained a lot in that winter and the mud and dampness was a worry to everyone. Our driveway became an absolute bog and so Bruce contacted the Works Department about some kind of help with our drive. I might add that Canberra was only a small place in those days and mostly everyone knew or knew of, one another. Our request was granted. A large load of rocks was delivered to our driveway - as too was a sledgehammer with a little note from someone in the department with a great sense of humour - \'Good luck with the rocks Bruce\'!! So much for knowing someone in the Works Department.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Dorothy Holgate, Quinn Street, 1950-52 (contributed 1996)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '\'Good luck with the rocks, Bruce!\'', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '179-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-10-04 07:15:37', '2021-10-04 07:15:37', '', 179, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?p=180', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(181, 1, '2021-10-04 07:34:36', '2021-10-04 07:34:36', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The new and growing population of Canberra included construction workers and workers in a wide range of service industries as well as transferred public servants. People from all these groups were on the Government housing list and when houses like the Tocumwals became available, getting somewhere to live was generally more important than location or style of house. The old Canberra hierarchies of status and position were not evident in the early years of the Tocumwal houses.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {"className":"is-style-wide"} -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator is-style-wide"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">The first to be handed over</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We moved into Hart Street in November 1948. I was in hospital with my first born, then my husband was offered the house.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/the-first-to-be-handed-over/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Block 5 Section 36</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Transported by father-in-law in his Jaguar our family arrived at Block 5 section 36, O’Connor. No street, footpath or hedge. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/block-5-section-36/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Just the house on a bare suburban block</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We moved into Quinn Street, O’Connor early June 1950. The road was unpaved, there were no footpaths, just the house</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/just-the-house-on-a-bare-suburban-block/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">The japonica hedge and other improvements</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first thing in any house I’ve ever been in is at least to stick in a geranium by the door. I don’t know whether I did that there but we certainly made a garden of sorts, straight away.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/the-japonica-hedge-and-other-improvements/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">We were glad to get the house</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We were glad to get the house and settled down and had our five children there.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/we-were-glad-to-get-the-house/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">‘Good luck with the rocks, Bruce!’</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It rained a lot in that winter and the mud and dampness was a worry to everyone. Our driveway became an absolute bog and so Bruce contacted the Works Department about some kind of help with our drive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/good-luck-with-the-rocks-bruce/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->', 'Early years of house in O\'Connor', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'early-years-of-house-in-oconnor', '', '', '2021-10-04 13:52:44', '2021-10-04 13:52:44', '', 11, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?page_id=181', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(182, 1, '2021-10-04 07:33:39', '2021-10-04 07:33:39', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After the bombing of Darwin, the United States and Australia made joint plans for Australian inland defence. The Tocumwal airfield was the largest and first of several large airfields planned for construction in relation to the the line of possible Japanese advance. It was built by the Australian Government (Australian Civil Construction Corps and Allied Works Council) on behalf of the United States Army Air Force between February and April 1942. Five thousand people were involved in the construction of the base which was designed to stage bombing raids and reconnaissance flights, as well as take the role of the first training centre in the South-West Pacific for Liberators. Not long after the ‘houses’ were erected at the end of the building process, the Battle of the Coral Sea halted the Japanese advance and the USAAF decided to move north to Townsville. The Royal Australian air force officially took over the running of Tocumwal in November 1942, establishing it as a hospital and training base.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>(Information from Thematic Study: WWII Aerodromes and associated structures in New South Wales, New South Wales Heritage Office, 2000, and military historians Dr Darryl McIntyre and Noel Flanagan)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {"className":"is-style-wide"} -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator is-style-wide"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'The origins of Canberra\'s \'Tocumwal\' houses', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '142-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-10-04 07:33:39', '2021-10-04 07:33:39', '', 142, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?p=182', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(183, 1, '2021-10-04 07:34:36', '2021-10-04 07:34:36', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The new and growing population of Canberra included construction workers and workers in a wide range of service industries as well as transferred public servants. People from all these groups were on the Government housing list and when houses like the Tocumwals became available, getting somewhere to live was generally more important than location or style of house. The old Canberra hierarchies of status and position were not evident in the early years of the Tocumwal houses.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Early years of house in O\'Connor', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '181-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-10-04 07:34:36', '2021-10-04 07:34:36', '', 181, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?p=183', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(184, 1, '2021-10-04 07:45:14', '2021-10-04 07:45:14', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I was born on 16 Jan 1949 in the (then) Canberra Community Hospital. My sister Diane Elizabeth Frame also was born there on 24 Nov 1951.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our parents were Harold William Frame and Jacqueline Maud Frame. In Canberra, initially they rented with Bernice and Bill Burns (a PMG Lineman) at 15(?) Bass Gardens, Griffith, then moved into 2 Lord St when the house became available. They were the first tenants. Dad was then working as a carpenter with the Commonwealth Department<br>of Works.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I remember a very popular sandpit in the kindergarten yard and a \'flying fox\' from \'upstairs\' in a shed in the school yard to (I think) somewhere near the sandpit. Another favourite pastime was collecting the grass when it was cut in the yard and cramming it into a holding bin on the back of one for my friends trikes. What he did with it when he got home, I can\'t imagine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You weren\'t anyone unless you had a Davy Crocket \'raccoon skin\' hat. A good cowboy outfit, or at least a pistol and holster cap gun, also was de rigeur. When I was about 7-8, cowboys and Indians were all the go. At one stage, about age 7 probably, I had a cowboy suit and hat. Mum has a photo of me and David Peak, both in cowboy outfits, sitting in the grass common area at the end of Lord St.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because Belconnen Way was not built, Miller St was the last street before Black Mountain. Groups of us would go up onto Black Mountain to build \'cowboy forts\'. These generally were just little squares with low walls made of fallen timber etc. I don\'t think we went too far into the bush, but far enough for us to play out of sight of the houses. I remember someone turning over an old piece of galvanised iron one day and finding a nest of redback spiders: I don\'t think we stopped running until we crossed Miller St.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As long as I can remember, we used to be able to turn on the fire hydrant at the end of Lord St. (A long-gone luxury - fire-fighters now bring their own spanners). We used to all build little dams in the gutter all the way down the street, make a bunch of stick and leaf little \'boats\', then turn on the hydrant. The object was to see how long your dam could last and how fast your boat would go.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\'Cracker Night\', Empire Day 24 May (my parents wedding anniversary), was an occassion that everyone joined in. Someone, I don\'t know who, used to arrange a bonfire in the common area between Lord and Way Streets and everyone went along and brought their crackers. It was also when you had penny and threepenny bungers available to buy and blow up post boxes, and tom thumb strings to scare the dogs and cats.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In winter, if you wanted something to do that was great fun and annoyed your mother, you could always go out in the morning and jump on the puddles to break the ice. In the early 50s, the road and footpath must not have been paved properly as I can remember lots of good puddles frozen over - not deep ones, but they still had a bit of muddy water in the bottom.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My main friend was Alan Harding, who lived at 64 Miller St next to the fire shed in the common area, on our side. His father was with the CSIRO. Alan went to school with me until I moved to Darwin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Ian Frame, 2 Lord Street, 1948-59 (contributed 1996)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Cowboys and cracker nights', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cowboys-and-cracker-nights', '', '', '2021-10-04 07:45:14', '2021-10-04 07:45:14', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?p=184', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(185, 1, '2021-10-04 07:43:50', '2021-10-04 07:43:50', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first children to grow up in the Tocumwal houses were part of the post-war baby boom. They were often members of large families - memories of the number of kids in any one of the cul-de-sacs of 12 or 14 houses, include countings of over 50. Many of them played together as children and young adolescents. The neighbourhood plan around the park and the easy access between houses facilitated these connections. The bush of Black Mountain and O\'Connor Ridge on the other side of Miller Street offered territory for exploring and games, and collecting firewood for cracker night bonfires in the park. Adult parties included neighbourhood friends and others from further afield.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator {"className":"is-style-wide"} -->\n<hr class="wp-block-separator is-style-wide"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:block {"ref":221} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Dressing up</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My mum made a nun’s habit for me. I used to dress up and pretend to teach school, usually to a class of dolls.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/dressing-up/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Suicide Hill</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Up from my place there was what we used to call Suicide Hill. It was the gully that runs parallel to Fairfax Street and which is now the stormwater drain.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/suicide-hill/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Visiting</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first encounter that I had, personally, with the Tocumwal houses, was in 1948, when they were very new. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/visiting/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Todd Street ceilidhs</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When Barty’s children were 21 we had a party and when my children were 21 we had a party and just for the hell of it we had a party.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/todd-street-ceilidhs/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Square dancing</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we went square dancing sometimes they’d come back here and it’d be nothing to have 40 or 50 people in the lounge room here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/square-dancing/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Dances and a keg of beer</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We used to have a party occasionally. Alice was very good on the accordion.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/dances-and-a-keg-of-beer/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->\n\n<!-- wp:columns -->\n<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"fontSize":"normal"} -->\n<h2 class="has-normal-font-size">Sunday at the Raccosta’s</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the early days, because there were so few of us, every Sunday afternoon, the Italian families would get together in our big room and have a dance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class="wp-block-buttons"><!-- wp:button {"fontSize":"small"} -->\n<div class="wp-block-button has-custom-font-size has-small-font-size"><a class="wp-block-button__link" href="http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/sunday-at-the-raccostas/">View</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column -->\n\n<!-- wp:column -->\n<div class="wp-block-column"></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns -->', 'Parties and pastimes during the first twenty years', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'parties-and-pastimes-during-the-first-twenty-years', '', '', '2021-10-04 13:21:42', '2021-10-04 13:21:42', '', 11, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?page_id=185', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(186, 1, '2021-10-04 07:43:50', '2021-10-04 07:43:50', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first children to grow up in the Tocumwal houses were part of the post-war baby boom. They were often members of large families - memories of the number of kids in any one of the cul-de-sacs of 12 or 14 houses, include countings of over 50. Many of them played together as children and young adolescents. The neighbourhood plan around the park and the easy access between houses facilitated these connections. The bush of Black Mountain and O\'Connor Ridge on the other side of Miller Street offered territory for exploring and games, and collecting firewood for cracker night bonfires in the park. Adult parties included neighbourhood friends and others from further afield.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Parties and pastimes during the first twenty years', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '185-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-10-04 07:43:50', '2021-10-04 07:43:50', '', 185, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?p=186', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(187, 1, '2021-10-04 07:45:14', '2021-10-04 07:45:14', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I was born on 16 Jan 1949 in the (then) Canberra Community Hospital. My sister Diane Elizabeth Frame also was born there on 24 Nov 1951.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our parents were Harold William Frame and Jacqueline Maud Frame. In Canberra, initially they rented with Bernice and Bill Burns (a PMG Lineman) at 15(?) Bass Gardens, Griffith, then moved into 2 Lord St when the house became available. They were the first tenants. Dad was then working as a carpenter with the Commonwealth Department<br>of Works.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I remember a very popular sandpit in the kindergarten yard and a \'flying fox\' from \'upstairs\' in a shed in the school yard to (I think) somewhere near the sandpit. Another favourite pastime was collecting the grass when it was cut in the yard and cramming it into a holding bin on the back of one for my friends trikes. What he did with it when he got home, I can\'t imagine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You weren\'t anyone unless you had a Davy Crocket \'raccoon skin\' hat. A good cowboy outfit, or at least a pistol and holster cap gun, also was de rigeur. When I was about 7-8, cowboys and Indians were all the go. At one stage, about age 7 probably, I had a cowboy suit and hat. Mum has a photo of me and David Peak, both in cowboy outfits, sitting in the grass common area at the end of Lord St.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Because Belconnen Way was not built, Miller St was the last street before Black Mountain. Groups of us would go up onto Black Mountain to build \'cowboy forts\'. These generally were just little squares with low walls made of fallen timber etc. I don\'t think we went too far into the bush, but far enough for us to play out of sight of the houses. I remember someone turning over an old piece of galvanised iron one day and finding a nest of redback spiders: I don\'t think we stopped running until we crossed Miller St.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As long as I can remember, we used to be able to turn on the fire hydrant at the end of Lord St. (A long-gone luxury - fire-fighters now bring their own spanners). We used to all build little dams in the gutter all the way down the street, make a bunch of stick and leaf little \'boats\', then turn on the hydrant. The object was to see how long your dam could last and how fast your boat would go.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\'Cracker Night\', Empire Day 24 May (my parents wedding anniversary), was an occassion that everyone joined in. Someone, I don\'t know who, used to arrange a bonfire in the common area between Lord and Way Streets and everyone went along and brought their crackers. It was also when you had penny and threepenny bungers available to buy and blow up post boxes, and tom thumb strings to scare the dogs and cats.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In winter, if you wanted something to do that was great fun and annoyed your mother, you could always go out in the morning and jump on the puddles to break the ice. In the early 50s, the road and footpath must not have been paved properly as I can remember lots of good puddles frozen over - not deep ones, but they still had a bit of muddy water in the bottom.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>My main friend was Alan Harding, who lived at 64 Miller St next to the fire shed in the common area, on our side. His father was with the CSIRO. Alan went to school with me until I moved to Darwin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Ian Frame, 2 Lord Street, 1948-59 (contributed 1996)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Cowboys and cracker nights', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '184-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-10-04 07:45:14', '2021-10-04 07:45:14', '', 184, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?p=187', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(188, 1, '2021-10-04 07:46:40', '2021-10-04 07:46:40', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For a long as I can remember there has been a cross on the chimney. The chimney featured in many of our games, we practiced tennis using the cross as a marker, and played various ball games (especially 7\'s). We often used the chimney as home base for hide and seek. There could be as many as 50 kids playing hide and seek at dusk.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>David remembers marking out the existing cross with glue. A fire proof glue was used to remark the cross on the chimney. Dad said it would never wear off - guess what he was right. Just recently (September 1996) when visiting Todd Street, I noted with interest that the cross still looked the same.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Maureen Bourne (nee Battisson), 4 Todd Street, 1953-76 (contributed 1996)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'The cross on the chimney', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-cross-on-the-chimney', '', '', '2021-10-04 07:46:40', '2021-10-04 07:46:40', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/WP/example/Wordpress/?p=188', 0, 'post', '', 0),
